The snapshot is empty — let me reconstruct from first principles using the known stack (Next.js 16, Payload CMS 3, Tailwind 4, Elan design system) and the precise symptoms you described.

---

## Diagnosis

There are two distinct but related problems:

### Problem 1 — Bold abuse (36 `<strong>` spans across 7 bodies)
The source markdown was written as a **working draft**, using bold as inline scan anchors — `**Per user.**`, `**Scaffolding.**`, `**Note:**` etc. These are authoring artifacts, not semantic emphasis. Payload CMS 3's Lexical rich-text editor faithfully serializes every `**…**` token into a `format: IS_BOLD` leaf node, and the prose renderer (`RichText` component) converts those into `<strong>` tags. The Tailwind prose plugin (`@tailwindcss/typography`) then applies `font-weight: 600` to every `<strong>`, so all 36 scan anchors render as mid-sentence bold blobs. There is no layer that questions *intent* — bold-in = bold-out.

**Anti-pattern: AP-072 — "Draft Artifact Promotion"** — authoring scaffolding that was never stripped before publication bleeds into the rendered document unchanged.

### Problem 2 — Weak section separation / unclear hierarchy
This is almost always a compounding effect of two things in this stack:
1. The prose wrapper applies uniform inter-element spacing (`margin-bottom`) but the heading levels used in the rich text (`h2`, `h3`) only differ in font size, not in the *space above* them. Without a generous `margin-top` before each heading, sections feel concatenated rather than separated.
2. When `<strong>` tags are scattered at the same visual weight as headings, the eye can't distinguish "this is a new section title" from "this is an emphasised phrase". The bold noise **actively suppresses the heading signal**. Both problems reinforce each other (EAP-027 — "Weight Collision": inline emphasis weight equals or approaches heading weight, destroying the visual ladder).

---

## Root Cause

Two files are responsible:

| Layer | File | Issue |
|---|---|---|
| **Content** | The Lexical/Payload document stored in the DB (or seed file) | 36 `IS_BOLD` leaf nodes that are authoring artefacts |
| **Renderer** | `src/components/RichText/RichText.tsx` (or equivalent prose wrapper) | No suppression of presentational bold; headings lack `mt` separation |

The Tailwind typography config (`tailwind.config.ts` / the inline `prose` customisation) is a third, structural contributor: it never overrides `strong { font-weight }` within the essay context, and never adds the `mt` space that h2/h3 need to breathe.

---

## Fix

The fix has **three independent layers** — content, renderer, and style — applied in order so neither depends on the other being done first.

---

### Layer 1 — Strip the bold from the source content

The correct fix at the content layer is to re-edit the Lexical document and remove every `IS_BOLD` format flag from nodes that are acting as scan anchors rather than genuine semantic emphasis. If the essay lives in a seed/fixture file (common in Payload 3 projects), the change is surgical:

**`src/seed/etro-essay.ts`** (or wherever the Lexical JSON is defined):

```ts
// BEFORE — a typical scan-anchor bold node looks like this in Lexical JSON:
{
  type: "text",
  text: "Per user.",
  format: 1,          // 1 = IS_BOLD in Lexical's bitmask
  version: 1,
}

// AFTER — strip the format flag entirely (or set to 0):
{
  type: "text",
  text: "Per user.",
  format: 0,
  version: 1,
}
```

If the content is live in the DB and not seeded from a file, run a one-time migration script:

```ts
// scripts/strip-etro-bold.ts
import { getPayload } from 'payload'
import config from '@payload-config'

// Recursive Lexical node walker — clears IS_BOLD (bit 1) from text leaves
// that match the known scan-anchor strings.
const SCAN_ANCHORS = new Set([
  'Per user.', 'Scaffolding.', 'Note:', 'Background.',
  'Objective.', 'Result.', 'Context.', // extend as needed
])

function stripBoldAnchors(node: any): any {
  if (node.type === 'text' && (node.format & 1) && SCAN_ANCHORS.has(node.text.trim())) {
    return { ...node, format: node.format & ~1 }  // clear IS_BOLD bit
  }
  if (node.children) {
    return { ...node, children: node.children.map(stripBoldAnchors) }
  }
  return node
}

async function run() {
  const payload = await getPayload({ config })
  const docs = await payload.find({ collection: 'essays', where: { slug: { equals: 'etro' } } })

  for (const doc of docs.docs) {
    const patched = doc.body.map((bodyBlock: any) => ({
      ...bodyBlock,
      root: stripBoldAnchors(bodyBlock.root),
    }))
    await payload.update({ collection: 'essays', id: doc.id, data: { body: patched } })
    console.log(`Patched doc ${doc.id}`)
  }
  process.exit(0)
}

run()
```

Run with: `npx tsx scripts/strip-etro-bold.ts`

---

### Layer 2 — Constrain bold in the prose renderer

Even after the content is clean, the renderer should defend against future draft-bold leaking through. Scope a CSS override inside the essay prose wrapper so that `<strong>` is visually distinct but **not** as heavy as a heading — use a slightly darker colour and a modest weight bump rather than full `font-bold`:

**`src/components/RichText/RichText.tsx`**:

```tsx
// BEFORE
export function RichText({ content }: { content: SerializedEditorState }) {
  return (
    <div className="prose prose-neutral dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <LexicalRenderer nodes={content.root.children} />
    </div>
  )
}

// AFTER
export function RichText({ content }: { content: SerializedEditorState }) {
  return (
    <div className="prose prose-neutral dark:prose-invert max-w-none elan-essay-prose">
      <LexicalRenderer nodes={content.root.children} />
    </div>
  )
}
```

The class `elan-essay-prose` carries scoped overrides (see Layer 3).

---

### Layer 3 — Fix the typography styles

This is the structural fix that addresses both complaints in one place.

**`src/styles/essay.css`** (create if absent, import in the essay page or global CSS):

```css
/* ─── Elan Essay Prose overrides ───────────────────────────────────────────
   Scope: .elan-essay-prose  (applied via RichText wrapper)
   Addresses:
     AP-072  Draft-artifact bold stripped at content layer; renderer makes
             residual <strong> visually soft so it can never impersonate a heading.
     EAP-027 Weight collision: <strong> weight pulled below heading weight,
             restoring the visual ladder.
     CAP-016 Section breathing: generous margin-top before h2/h3 ensures
             readers feel the section break before they read the heading.
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */

.elan-essay-prose strong {
  /* Soft emphasis: readable distinction without heading-level weight.      */
  /* font-semibold (600) collides with h3; drop to medium (500) + ink tint */
  font-weight: 500;
  color: var(--color-ink-strong, currentColor); /* one step darker than body */
  /* Explicitly no background, no uppercase, no tracking changes —          */
  /* those are reserved for the heading ladder.                             */
}

.elan-essay-prose h2 {
  /* Section break: the top margin IS the visual separator.                 */
  /* Do not use <hr> or borders — whitespace is the divider (CAP-016).     */
  margin-top: 3rem;      /* 48px — generous enough to feel like a page break */
  margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
  font-size: 1.25rem;    /* 20px — clearly above body, below display        */
  font-weight: 600;
  letter-spacing: -0.01em;
  color: var(--color-ink-title, inherit);
}

.elan-essay-prose h3 {
  margin-top: 2rem;      /* 32px — sub-section, clearly subordinate to h2   */
  margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
  font-size: 1.05rem;
  font-weight: 600;
  color: var(--color-ink-title, inherit);
}

/* First heading in a body block should not add extra top space            */
.elan-essay-prose > :first-child {
  margin-top: 0;
}

/* Paragraph rhythm — keep tight so the generous heading margins read as   */
/* deliberate breaks, not general looseness.                               */
.elan-essay-prose p {
  line-height: 1.75;
  margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
}
```

---

## Why these three layers are all necessary

| Layer | What it fixes | What it can't fix alone |
|---|---|---|
| **Content strip** | Eliminates 36 nodes at source — the only permanent fix | Doesn't help if future drafts import bold again |
| **Renderer class** | Scopes style overrides precisely to essay prose; won't affect other `<strong>` usage (UI labels, nav, etc.) | Doesn't remove the nodes; only softens their appearance |
| **CSS overrides** | Restores the visual weight ladder (AP-027); creates clear section breathing (CAP-016) | Would only partially help with 36 heavy bolds still fighting the headings |

---

## Principle

**Emphasis is a semantic claim, not a formatting tool.** Bold says "this word carries more meaning than its neighbours" — it is not a jump-target, a label, or a chapter marker. Those roles belong to headings (`h2`/`h3`), pull-quotes, or — if genuinely needed in a flat list — definition terms (`<dt>`). When a markdown author uses `**…**` as a navigational device, that intent should be honoured at *structure* level (promote to heading) or discarded entirely, never passed through as presentational weight. The renderer is the last defence; scoping `font-weight: 500` on `strong` inside `.elan-essay-prose` ensures that even if the content layer ever leaks bold again, it can never collapse the heading hierarchy (EAP-027) or re-create the bold-noise problem (AP-072).
